<p><ent>Fond</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Fond
<hw>Fond</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos>
<adjf>Fonder</adjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos>
<adjf>Fondest</adjf>.]</amorph> <ety>[For <ets>fonned</ets>, p. p. of
OE. <ets>fonnen</ets> to be foolish. See <er>Fon</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>Foolish; silly; simple; weak.</def>
<mark>[Archaic]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Grant I may never prove so <qex>fond</qex>⟦br⟧
To trust man on his oath or bond.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Foolishly tender and loving; weakly indulgent;
over-affectionate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Affectionate; loving; tender; -- in a good sense;
<as>as, a <ex>fond</ex> mother or wife</as>.</def>
<rj><au>Addison.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Loving; much pleased; affectionately regardful,
indulgent, or desirous; longing or yearning; -- followed by
<xex>of</xex> (formerly also by <xex>on</xex>).</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q> More <qex>fond</qex> on her than she upon her love.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q> You are as <qex>fond</qex> of grief as of your child.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q> A great traveler, and <qex>fond</qex> of telling his
adventures.</q> <rj><qau>Irving.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Doted on; regarded with affection.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q> Nor fix on <qex>fond</qex> abodes to circumscribe thy prayer.</q>
<rj><qau>Byron.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Trifling; valued by folly; trivial.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fond</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Fond
<hw>Fond</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To caress; to fondle.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q> The Tyrian hugs and <qex>fonds</qex> thee on her breast.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fond</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Fond
<hw>Fond</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To be fond; to dote.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fond</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Fond
<hw>Fond</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. L.
<ets>fundus</ets>. See <er>Fund</er>.]</ety> <mark>[Obs., or used as a
French word]</mark> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Foundation; bottom;
groundwork;</def> <specif>specif.:</specif> <sd>(a)</sd> <fld>(Lace
Making)</fld> <def>The ground.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <fld>(Cookery)</fld>
<def>The broth or juice from braised flesh or fish, usually served as a
sauce.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Fund, stock, or store.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fondant</ent>⟦br⟧
